<DOC><DOCNO> AP880420-0214 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-88 1803EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     04-20 0323</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0331</SECOND><HEAD>Snow in Michigan, New Hampshire, Nevada</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Spring snowstorms blanketed parts of Michigan, New Hampshire andNevada on Wednesday, while mountain areas in the West braced forsnow.   Rain reached from California across eastern Oregon, northernNevada, southern Idaho, northwest Wyoming and southeast Montana.The rain changed to snow in higher elevations.   A winter storm warning was posted for the central and southwestmountains of Idaho, and a winter storm watch was in effect forhigher elevations of the central and northern mountains of Arizona.   Snow fell in the California mountains, and heavy rain at lowerelevations prompted flood advisories for some urban areas. Rainalso dampened northern Illinois, northern Indiana, northwest Ohio,southern Michigan and southeast Wisconsin.   Heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 2 p.m. EDTincluded 1.05 inches at the San Diego Naval Air Station and 0.54inch at Imperial Beach, Calif.   During the same period, 5 inches of snow fell at MountWashington, N.H., and 1 inch at Marquette, Mich. Austin, Nev., got3 inches in the morning.   Temperatures at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 30 degrees at SaranacLake, N.Y., to 91 at San Angelo, Tex. The nation's morning low was17 at Warroad, Minn.   Thursday's forecast called for rain, changing to snow in themountains, from the inland portions of the northern and centralPacific Coast to southern California, from Idaho to Arizona andMontana and from northwest of Colorado to South Dakota and northernNebraska.   High temperatures were expected to reach the mid-30s over themountains of northern Arizona; the 40s and 50s from New Englandacross the Great Lakes, the upper Mississippi Valley, the northernPlains, the Rockies, the northern plateau and the Great Basin; the80s from South Carolina across Florida, the central Gulf states,the lower Mississippi Valley and much of the southern Plains; the90s over western Texas, and the 60s and 70s elsewhere.</TEXT></DOC>